text: Perfect timing for me - the Beatles came out when I was 13, and ready for new music.  Would they be popular today, starting out? Impossible to answer - they wouldn't be the same people, with the same background. It's like asking if, say, Billie Eilish would have been popular in 1964. She surely wouldn't have had green hair!  And what if they were from a non-English country? Even Germany? Could they sell that sound in the States? Or GB? It would be an uphill battle. But even so - as good as they were, they had plenty of competition back then.  I'm glad I remember them! (but could I remember all the words?) And I loved the movie. Especially Lilly! And that painter who lived on the beach...

text: Am I the only one that noticed the plot similarities between this movie and the movie ‚ÄúShark Tale‚Äù?  Now we all know which one of these movies is better than the other. But think about it, there are actually a lot of plot similarities between these two movies:  - Jack Malik starts out as an unsuccessful musician, that no one cares for. Oscar starts out as a whale washer that no one cares for. - Jack realizes, after the blackout, that the Beatles no longer exist. He then takes full-on advantage of this by making a music career out of their songs, becoming the biggest and most successful ‚Äúmusician‚Äù to ever live. - Oscar realizes, after the anchor kills Frankie, that everyone thinks he killed the shark himself. He then takes full on advantage of this by becoming the ‚ÄúShark Slayer‚Äù, that everyone in the ocean automatically idolizes.  - There is a gold digger in each of this movie that become ‚Äúassociated‚Äù with the protagonist just because they want to be big and famous too (Deborah in Jack‚Äôs case, Lola in Oscar‚Äôs) - There is a woman in love with both protagonists that never confess their feelings for him until it‚Äôs too late, but end up with him anyways for plot (Ellie in Jack‚Äôs case, Angie in Oscar‚Äôs) - Both of the lies that they live later come back to haunt them, and they learn and grow from the mistake of living a lie. They later go back to their normal lives, and realize that they‚Äôre the same person that they‚Äôve always been, and don‚Äôt need to be rich and famous to be a somebody.   Am I really the only one that‚Äôs noticed all the similarities? Because, in a way, these two are practically the same movie.

text: It's an interesting premise, but I honestly wonder if The Beatles music would have this much of an impact in today's music landscape.  The main reason The Beatles were so successful and influential was because of their timing.  They were innovators who basically created rock music. And you rarely see screaming teenage girls chasing after rock bands anymore.

text: Yesterday could've been the sweet antidote in a world filled with sequels and blockbusters, but nothing is more disappointing than to see a well-accomplished director as Boyle screw it all up. The direction is all over the place with inter-titles and unbelievable scenes that won't fly in the world we live in right now. It is too realistic to be set in a fantasy world and the film never pulls you in completely. Even the funny one liners and McKinnon's delightful comedic punches as a stereotypical Hollywood agent, can't save how ordinary "Yesterday" feels. And if you're really here for the music, I have to disappoint you. The few music montages are not even worth the admission, since most of the performances get cut short. Just let it be.

text: That ending with the 'Hey Dude' shows just how much this premise would not make sense. If we all woke up tomorrow and NOBODY had any recollection of the Beatles' music; it would never become that popular against the modern day music. They're still popular today because parents and grandparents have passed them down; but nobody would turn away from their modern music to listen to songs that sound like they should have been written 40 to 50 years ago. And how is he supposed to explain the more "out there" songs like: 'Yellow Submarine', 'Strawberry Fields Forever', 'Lucy in the Sky with Diamonds', 'I am the Walrus', etc.? Plus, there's no trace of the Beatles or their songs... you're expecting me to believe that he knows every word, every note, and every chord to EVERY single Beatles song? If he's that much of a musical prodigy he wouldn't need this "miracle" to happen to become famous. The only way this movie will work is if it's all a coma dream from being hit by that truck.

text: The magic of The Beatles was also culturally the time they rose to fame in. I honestly wonder if someone was writing these kinds songs today, would they be as wildly popular? We've shifted culturally to so many different styles and genres since then. What is considered "popular music" and "a hit" is vastly different from the 60s. Not saying The Beatles weren't one of the greatest bands to ever live, I just think there is so much more at play then the music itself. PS: I totally understand this is just a movie, and it honestly seems like a great concept, this is just the anthropologist in me analyzing lol.

text: Seems awesome, but it has cultural flaws. Half of what you see on screen was in some way, shape or form inspired by The Beatles. The things people wear, the places they go to, the people you see. Heck, even Ed Sheeran (in my opinion a very terrible songwriter) himself is inspired by The Beatles. They also mentioned Coldplay, which of course wouldn‚Äôt have come to be without The Beatles. It‚Äôs just a fact. The Beatles inspired a generation which has inspired the next, ours and others yet to come. This seems like a great film, but it doesn‚Äôt do justice to show you how phenomenal and culturally defying The Beatles actually were.

People would tell him, 'hey, that sounded good, nice job,' and that would be it. He'd get 30 plays on his youtube videos. The only way to get anyone to care about your music anymore is through likes, posts, manipulating your sound, and exploiting yourself. text: The thinly disguised story of Theodor W. Adorno, or "cultrural appropriation on steroids." Nothing is new under the sun.  Those songs came down to us through generations of playing and imitation.  Classical composers used the peasant songs of their ancestors, adding the innovations of orchestral instrumentation.  Adorno back engineered Classical music to find the traditional folk songs, and sold them for use by The Beatles and dozens of other popular musicians in the sixties and early seventies.  He kept the rights to the music, which is really why The Beatles didn't own their music.  People said Adorno could crank out dozens of songs in an hour. Those songs were tried and tested by generations of our ancestors, selected by Classical composers as the best of the best, and mined from their symphonies. They seem to want to tell us the truth by drips and drabs.
author: Timothy Kuring

text: Let me just start by saying this, I'm never one to watch trailers really, but I accidentally clicked on an ad for this on Twitter. No clue why I didn't just click off, but I watched it all the way through.  I've never listened to a whole lot of Beatles music, but this trailer made me excited about a movie for a band I'd never really even listened to.   As such, I listened to Yesterday for the namesake of this film, and I shed a few tears. It wasn't something stunning or over the top, it just strikes all of the right chords in my heart.  This has a lot of potential to be something special, and I hope that they really don't let us down. Even if the trailer is a bit generic, there's no denying the charm and spectacle that it inspires. I've got my hopes that even if this isn't really the greatest    TL:DR: I accidentally watched this trailer, and now I'm excited about The Beatles and this movie.

text: The idea for this movie was kinda pinched from the British BBC1 1990s TV show: "Goodnight Sweetheart"; in which an unknown young male London musician from the 1990s discovered a kind of time-gate in his den which took him back to the same location in World War II.  He visited it every episode, and the main thing was that he mainly went to a pub there, and played Beatles songs on its piano which people loved, and they would say: "It's great but I've never heard of it.", to which he would say "You will."  In the end, he took the credit that he'd written them himself.  So this looks like another Gen. Y copy of an older, truly original idea, simply modernised with 'the Mandela effect' scenario.  Nonetheless, it might be fun to watch, but they should be paying royalties to Laurence Marks & Maurice Gran (or their  heirs).

To back this up, in the Abbey Road album cover, one out of the four Beatles is barefoot (Paul), and there is one other Beatle, (Ringo), who is the only one of them wearing black shoes. One of the two men standing in that doorway are barefoot, and the other one is wearing black shoes. Are you guys starting to see a connection? Backed up by the fact that Paul and Ringo are the last surviving Beatles, piecing to together all the clues helps you build a bigger picture. Otherwise, why would someone walk into a talk show barefoot, unless it was to help build a bigger picture.

If they wouldn't exist, it would have been another "beatles" in the 60,s even 70,s that would have experimented with music. Therefore the whole film doesn't make sense and its gonna be full of "funny" gags and that's it. No coldplay without beatles (as coldplay is mentioned in the video) at least they would sound different. So the alternative present in this movie should have been very different. text: At the end of the trailer for this film we see that he's on a talk show and two men are claiming to be the writers of the songs. That's obviously going to be Paul McCartney and Ringo Starr. So what if we discover, this world in which the beatles never happened was something that the original remaining members actually wished for because the trappings of fame and celebrity were just too much. They just wanted to live a normal life for the rest of their days. But at the same time they're wishing for this, this dude is wishing to be the next beatles. So it becomes this sort of Freaky Friday scenario. Where the dude got his wish to become one of the greatest artists to exist, but he slowly turns into somebody thinking he's better than he is. So he loses the girl, then realises how the music industry doesn't actually care about the artists or the music they make. And the movie becomes sort of about how, the beatles couldn't exist today, because the music industry would have too much influence over what they would sound like. (I.e Hey Jude becomes Hey Dude). So this man goes out to find the real beatles and they work to change things back to the way they were. Probably by playing Yesterday or something. And then he gets the girl, happy ending. But my point is this movie seems really silly but there could be a lot of really interesting themes. Like, what is influence vs plagiarism, or how giant record labels are soul sucking, and how fame changes people. So it could be really interesting. Although presumably in this world, John Lennon wasn't brutally assassinated and was just sort of, hit by a car instead or something. So I don't know how they're going to cover that subject in a way that doesn't feel tasteless. but we'll see.

text: The fact that so many books still name the Beatles as "the greatest or most significant or most influential" rock band ever only tells you how far rock music still is from becoming a serious art. Jazz critics have long recognized that the greatest jazz musicians of all times are Duke Ellington and John Coltrane, who were not the most famous or richest or best sellers of their times, let alone of all times. Classical critics rank the highly controversial Beethoven over classical musicians who were highly popular in courts around Europe. Rock critics are still blinded by commercial success. The Beatles sold more than anyone else (not true, by the way), therefore they must have been the greatest. Jazz critics grow up listening to a lot of jazz music of the past, classical critics grow up listening to a lot of classical music of the past. Rock critics are often totally ignorant of the rock music of the past, they barely know the best sellers. No wonder they will think that the Beatles did anything worthy of being saved.
author: Yaso Magatsuhi
